hout federal collecting institutions. As Indigenous communities encounter the documentary traces of imperialism while attempting to reclaim what is theirs, this timely work shines a light on access to and return of cultural heritage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCataloging of archival materialsvCase studies. 0aCataloging of special collections in librariesvCase studies. 0aEthnological museums and collectionsvCase studies. 0aIndians of North AmericaxMaterial culturevCase studies. 0aIndiansxMaterial culturevCase studies. 0aMuseums and IndiansvCase studies. 0aMuseumsxCollection managementvCase studies. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486394040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774863940423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774863940/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127473-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-141765-3  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles